\section{Obtaining BioTime data}{

BioTime (\url{https://biotime.st-andrews.ac.uk}) is a global database of
biodiversity time-series assembled from published studies.  Data are
provided as per-study CSVs -- one file per study -- and are \strong{not} available
via a query API.  To download a study:
\enumerate{
\item Go to \url{https://biotime.st-andrews.ac.uk/home.php} and register for a
free account.
\item Browse or search the study list to find studies relevant to your taxon
and region.  Each study has a numeric STUDY_ID (e.g. 595).
\item On the study page, click \strong{Download data} to save the CSV
(typically named \verb{raw_data_<STUDY_ID>.csv}).
\item Note the STUDY_ID -- pass it to the \code{study_id} argument so that
\code{datasetID} is populated correctly in the output.
}

\strong{Citation:} BioTime requires that you cite both the database and the
original study.  The DOI for the BioTime database is
10.1111/geb.12729 (Dornelas et al. 2018, \emph{Global Ecology and Biogeography}).
Per-study citations are shown on each study's BioTime page.
}

\section{Column mapping}{

BioTime per-study CSVs use the following columns, which are mapped to
Darwin Core:

\describe{
\item{\code{valid_name}}{-> \code{scientificName}}
\item{\code{LATITUDE}}{-> \code{decimalLatitude}}
\item{\code{LONGITUDE}}{-> \code{decimalLongitude}}
\item{\code{ABUNDANCE}}{-> \code{organismQuantity}; \code{organismQuantityType} set to
\code{"abundance"}}
\item{\code{BIOMAS}}{-> \code{biotime_biomass} (non-DwC passthrough; note the
one-s spelling in BioTime source files)}
\item{\code{DAY}, \code{MONTH}, \code{YEAR}}{-> \code{day}, \code{month}, \code{year}}
\item{\code{SAMPLE_DESC}}{-> \code{eventID} (BioTime sample identifier)}
}

\code{occurrenceStatus} is set to \code{"present"} when \code{ABUNDANCE > 0} or
\code{BIOMAS > 0}, and \code{"absent"} otherwise.  Explicit zero records are
retained; filter with
\code{dplyr::filter(occurrenceStatus == "present")} if absences are not needed.
}

